<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/world <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/world" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 8 月 2 日星期三 19:08:32 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[Iran Begins Two-Day Shutdown as Heat Wave Worsens]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>气候变化给伊斯兰共和国带来了具体的安全挑战，该共和国因水资源短缺而面临动乱<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001104925"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828144?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">随着伊朗气温飙升，德黑兰的许多居民都呆在家里。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：WANA NEWS AGENCY/via REUTERS </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001104925"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sune-engel-rasmussen" itemprop="url" rel="author">Sune Engel Rasmussen</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name">Aresu Eqbali</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 2 日下午 2:11 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/iran-begins-two-day-shutdown-as-heat-wave-worsens-e756dcfc"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>德黑兰——周三，伊朗首都的气温超过华氏 100 度，整个德黑兰的社区变得一片寂静。</p><p>在政府宣布紧急关闭两天后，许多居民呆在家里，关闭银行、兑换商店和政府办公室，并呼吁私营企业效仿。向北，从城市通往较凉爽地区的道路上挤满了寻求避暑的人们。</p><p>周二宣布的全国放假是对越来越<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/rising-temperatures-turns-middle-east-region-into-climate-hot-spot-11663172120?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">频繁的热浪</a>袭击该国的不同寻常的反应，该国南部地区的气温已超过 120 华氏度。</p><p>卫生部建议儿童、老年人和有潜在健康问题的人留在室内。其他政府部门呼吁人们减少用电，除了早上和深夜之外不要使用高耗电的设备，以确保伊朗近9000万人口有足够的电力供应。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828142?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周三德黑兰气温升至 100 华氏度以上。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：WANA NEWS AGENCY/via REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>在宣布为期两天的特殊假期后，早在周二晚上，在首都北部山区和里海沿岸拥有度假屋的居民就纷纷坐上汽车。杂货店、餐馆和购物中心基本上保持营业，但首都内的交通明显比平时少。</p><p>在遭受全球变暖的地区，伊朗特别容易受到气候变化的影响。该地区以干旱和半干旱气候为主，降雨量和降雪量较少。</p><p>尽管<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/iraq-tests-u-s-sanctions-with-oil-for-gas-deal-with-iran-c318b917?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">美国的制裁</a>在一定程度上阻碍了伊朗减轻全球变暖影响的能力，但历届政府都未能投资于太阳能或更高效的农业技术等气候友好型举措。冬天，当冷空气笼罩着雾霾时，首都德黑兰就笼罩在黄色的薄雾中，这些薄雾是由陈旧的汽车喷出的劣质燃油排出的废气散发出来的。</p><p>伊朗当局警告说，西部乌尔米亚湖曾经是中东最大的湖泊，但自 20 世纪 90 年代中期以来一直在萎缩，如果大坝建设和其他农业项目不停止，该湖将面临完全干涸的风险。伊朗政府挖了一条 20 英里长的隧道，将附近盆地的水引入湖中。</p><p>然而，伊朗面临着一个难题，水坝和灌溉项目对于援助陷入困境的农业部门至关重要，该部门已经因气候变化的冲击而损失了数十亿美元。据联合国称，在伊朗这样的气候区，气温每升高一度，农作物产量就会减少 10%，在乌克兰战争已经严重<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/great-power-rivalry-looms-over-ukraine-grain-deal-3d2e0eb1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">扰乱全球粮食市场</a>的情况下，粮食安全将进一步恶化。</p><p>伊朗经济的其他部分——受到美国制裁的阻碍——没有能力适应。据该国商工矿农会称，截至 2022 年 3 月，停电导致该国非石油出口损失 70 亿至 80 亿美元。</p><p>今年气温飙升，七月成为有记录以来最热的月份，给整个中东地区带来了痛苦。</p><p>伊拉克去年延长了国定假日，以保护员工<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/as-iraq-tries-to-beat-the-heat-u-s-renews-sanctions-waiver-on-power-from-iran-11560860766?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">免受酷暑的影响</a>。预计本周该国大部分地区的气温将超过 120 华氏度，这将加剧该国状况不佳的电网的压力。</p><p>伊拉克的电力部分依赖从伊朗进口的天然气，但由于美国对德黑兰的制裁，伊拉克一直难以支付电费。随着债务的增加，伊朗在六月份削减了对伊拉克的天然气供应，导致其邻国在夏季酷暑来临之际陷入停电和电力短缺。巴格达政府上个月宣布了一项新的易货安排，根据该安排，伊拉克将向伊朗支付费用天然气与石油，考验着美国执行制裁的决心。</p><p>埃及上个月实行了计划性滚动限电措施，以缓解国家电网的压力，称在能源消耗激增的时期，每天的限电时间不会超过两个小时，并警告民众不要在一天中的某些时间使用电梯。政府还要求大多数公务员从周日开始每周远程工作一次，并鼓励私营公司采取类似措施。</p><p>在黎巴嫩，长期的电力配给加剧了酷热气温的影响。政府电网每天只提供几个小时的电力，使得生活在严重经济危机中的居民依赖私人发电机来降温。最近几周，该国还受到野火的困扰。</p><p>不过，伊朗当局对气候变化带来的安全挑战特别敏感。近年来，由于干旱和政府管理不善，政府面临着因水资源短缺而引发的日益激烈的骚乱。人们尤其在该国动荡和干旱的东南部地区以及中部城市伊斯法罕一条标志性河流干涸的河床进行抗议。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828143?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周二，一名男子在伊朗赞詹一家关门的商店里休息。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Rouzbeh Fouladi/ZUMA Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>锡斯坦-俾路支斯坦是阿富汗和巴基斯坦附近的边境地区，尤其令人担忧。这里是逊尼派穆斯林少数民族的家园<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/great-power-rivalry-looms-over-ukraine-grain-deal-3d2e0eb1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，他们对德黑兰中央政府有着敌对的历史</a>，也是去年席卷全国的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/iran-protests-hijab-11675177547?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">一系列抗议活动的</a>推动者。俾路支社区的饮用水日益短缺，周一，数百名居民走上街头抗议。</p><p>抗议活动的核心是与邻国阿富汗长达数十年的水资源冲突。</p><p>根据1973年的一项条约，两国共享源自阿富汗中部高地兴都库什山脉的赫尔曼德河的水源。多年来，伊朗当局一直指责现在由塔利班控制的阿富汗政府提供的水量低于其应有的份额，但阿富汗否认了这一指控。伊朗环境部负责人周三表示，阿富汗向伊朗提供的水资源不足伊朗应得的2%。</p><p>在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-taliban-are-here-the-final-days-before-kabuls-collapse-11629505499?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">塔利班接管阿富汗</a>之前，美国支持的阿什拉夫·加尼政府投资了数千万美元修建水坝项目，从赫尔曼德河引水灌溉阿富汗农田。</p><p>伊朗总统易卜拉欣·莱西5月警告塔利班不要侵犯伊朗人民的水权，并呼吁塔利班允许伊朗水文学家检查赫尔曼德河的水位，以确保伊朗的份额不被欺骗。几天后，边境爆发致命冲突，造成两名伊朗安全官员和一名塔利班边防人员死亡。</p><p>塔利班继续运营这些水坝。</p><p>与此同时，伊朗政府警告人们，如果高温持续下去，可能会进一步关闭。</p><p>伊朗内政部长艾哈迈德·瓦希迪表示，如果卫生当局认为有必要拯救生命，政府愿意在未来再次宣布公共假期。</p><p>据官方媒体报道，他说：“我们希望没有必要关闭国家。”</p><p>写信给 Sune Engel Rasmussen： <a href="mailto:sune.rasmussen@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">sune.rasmussen@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 02 Aug 2023 18:11:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/iran-begins-two-day-shutdown-as-heat-wave-worsens-e756dcfc</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/iran-begins-two-day-shutdown-as-heat-wave-worsens-e756dcfc<author><![CDATA[Sune Engel Rasmussen]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>气候变化</category><category>自然环境</category><category>全球/世界问题</category><category>自然资源稀缺</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>环境污染</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>气候变化</category><category>自然环境</category><category>全球的</category><category>世界问题</category><category>自然资源稀缺</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>环境污染</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Canadian Prime Minister Trudeau, Wife Separate]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>结婚18年，育有3个孩子<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001104884"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828395?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">尽管分居，贾斯汀·特鲁多和索菲·格雷瓜尔·特鲁多计划很快全家一起度假。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：anna Moneymaker/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001104884"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/paul-vieira" itemprop="url" rel="author">保罗·维埃拉</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 2 日下午 1:18（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/canada-prime-minister-trudeau-wife-sophie-gregoire-separate-6b7c6ed7"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>渥太华——加拿大总理贾斯汀·特鲁多和妻子索菲·格雷瓜尔·特鲁多周三表示，他们在结婚 18 年后分居。</p><p>这对夫妇在各自的 Instagram 账户上发表了声明。 51 岁的贾斯汀·特鲁多 (Justin Trudeau)<a href="https://www.instagram.com/p/CvctRHlrcL9/" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">在 Instagram 上表示：</a> “苏菲和我想分享这样一个事实：经过多次有意义且艰难的对话后，我们做出了分手的决定。”索菲·格雷瓜尔·特鲁多 (Sophie Grégoire Trudeau) 的<a href="https://www.instagram.com/p/CvctRb3uszw/" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">Instagram 帖子</a>几乎一模一样。他们都要求保护隐私。</p><p>总理办公室发表的另一份声明称，他们已经签署了合法分居协议，并确保遵守适当的法律和道德标准。</p><p>贾斯汀·特鲁多办公室的声明称：“他们仍然是一个亲密的家庭，索菲和总理致力于在安全、充满爱心和协作的环境中抚养孩子。” “父母双方都将持续出现在孩子的生活中，加拿大人可以经常看到家人在一起。”</p><p>他的办公室表示，从下周开始，一家人将一起度假。</p><p>贾斯汀·特鲁多 (Justin Trudeau) 和索菲·格雷瓜尔·特鲁多 (Sophie Grégoire Trudeau) 育有 3 个孩子：两个男孩（分别为 15 岁和 9 岁）和一个 14 岁的女儿。</p><p>这对夫妇最后一次公开露面是 7 月 1 日在渥太华，当时他们参加了庆祝加拿大 156 岁生日的仪式。</p><p>两人于 2003 年 6 月在一次慈善晚会上相识。贾斯汀·特鲁多 (Justin Trudeau) 在 2014 年的回忆录《共同点》(Common Ground) 中表示，他们整个晚上都在聊天、调情。几个月后，他们在蒙特利尔约会晚餐。 “我有一种头晕的感觉，索菲将是我约会过的最后一个女人，”他在回忆录中说道。</p><p>他们于 2005 年 5 月 28 日在蒙特利尔举行了婚礼，当地媒体称其为一场迷人的婚礼。仪式结束后，这对夫妇驾驶了一辆经过修复的 1960 年梅赛德斯-奔驰 300 SL 跑车，这辆跑车曾属于贾斯汀·特鲁多的父亲、前总理皮埃尔·特鲁多。</p><p></p><p> 48 岁的索菲·格雷瓜尔·特鲁多 (Sophie Grégoire Trudeau) 在蒙特利尔长大，并在蒙特利尔麦吉尔大学和蒙特利尔大学获得学位。她曾担任电视主持人，后来成为魁北克的娱乐记者。自由党网站将索菲·格雷瓜尔·特鲁多描述为多种事业的导师，包括青少年自尊、妇女和女童权利、饮食失调和心理健康。</p><p> “我可以马上告诉你，没有婚姻是容易的，”她在 2015 年 3 月接受《全球新闻》采访时说道，此时距离她的丈夫首次当选总理大约七个月。 “我几乎为我们经历过的困难感到自豪，是的，因为我们想要真实性。我们想要真相。”</p><p> 1977年5月，皮埃尔·特鲁多和妻子玛格丽特·特鲁多宣布分居。贾斯汀·特鲁多 (Justin Trudeau) 在 2014 年的回忆录中谈到这次分居时说道：“我记得那些糟糕的时光，就像一连串痛苦的情感瞬间。” “我父母的生活所施加的要求对他们的影响远远大于为人父母的普通压力。”</p><p>写信给保罗·维埃拉 (Paul Vieira)： <a href="mailto:Paul.Vieira@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Paul.Vieira@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 02 Aug 2023 17:18:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/canada-prime-minister-trudeau-wife-sophie-gregoire-separate-6b7c6ed7</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/canada-prime-minister-trudeau-wife-sophie-gregoire-separate-6b7c6ed7<author><![CDATA[Paul Vieira]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>贾斯汀·特鲁多</category><category>索菲·格雷瓜尔·特鲁多</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[A Drawn-Out Ukraine War Opens New Risks for China]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>北京预计出席和平会议可能表明其观点发生任何变化<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828293/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="周一，顿涅茨克俄罗斯控制区一处被毁的房屋。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>周一，顿涅茨克俄罗斯控制区一处被毁的房屋。亚历山大·埃尔莫琴科/路透社<span>亚历山大·埃尔莫琴科/路透社</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001104474"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001104474"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/james-t-areddy" itemprop="url" rel="author">詹姆斯·T·阿雷迪</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 2 日中午 12:37 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-drawn-out-ukraine-war-opens-new-risks-for-china-e5fe8b7c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>中国为俄罗斯总统<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/vladimir-putin">普京</a>对乌克兰的战争提供了重要的外交和经济支持。但随着冲突<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/as-war-becomes-grinding-fight-medics-battle-to-save-soldiers-in-ukraine-b04a976a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">进入第18个月，</a>双方都没有明显的胜利或投降迹象，北京面临着一系列日益复杂的风险，这使其更有动力推动莫斯科和基辅进行和平谈判。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/after-wagner-revolt-questions-of-blame-in-vladimir-putins-inner-circle-64c541ff?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">俄罗斯准军事组织瓦格纳</a>六月份令人震惊但短暂的叛乱引发了人们对普京掌权的新疑问，以及俄罗斯未来没有中国领导人习近平称之为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/story/xi-and-putin-a-friendship-forged-against-the-west-866dfcf1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">最好朋友的</a>独裁者的可能性。这也让人们重新关注北京支持莫斯科的风险。</p><p>据欧洲和美国官员称，预计习近平将派遣中国和平特使李辉出席乌克兰支持的国际会议，该会议旨在概述可能达成的和平协议的条款。这将标志着一个重大转变，因为北京方面没有参加该组织六月份在哥本哈根举行的第一次会议。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/saudi-arabia-to-host-ukraine-peace-talks-as-part-of-western-effort-to-woo-global-south-244f03f0?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">本周末在沙特阿拉伯举行的会议</a>旨在概述可能达成的和平协议的原则，与会者包括一系列同情基辅的世界大国，但不包括俄罗斯。据俄罗斯国家通讯社塔斯社报道，俄罗斯外交部发言人周三表示，这次会议是“一场骗局”，旨在建立一个反莫斯科联盟。</p><p>中国的参与将为美中就战争进行接触提供难得的机会，拜登总统的国家安全顾问杰克·沙利文预计也将出席。与会者将密切关注北京对这场冲突及其结局的思考发生变化的任何迹象。</p><p>北京在战时与俄罗斯的贸易问题上触碰<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-warns-china-could-arm-russia-as-ukraine-seeks-to-repel-advances-in-east-a5fd3e9e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">美国设定的红线，</a>导致其与西方的关系紧张，并引发了更多的审查，包括中国试图吸引的欧洲各国政府。中国继续表达对可能部署核武器的担忧——既<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-rebukes-russias-nuclear-threats-in-ukraine-for-first-time-11667585543?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">向莫斯科发出隐晦的警告</a>，又威胁西方限制对乌克兰的支持。</p><p>中国的不安在上个月的联合国大会上得到了体现，当时中国副常驻代表耿爽概述了对这场持久战争的严重担忧。耿爽表示，乌克兰危机拖延至今，当地没有任何缓和的迹象，军事逻辑依然盛行，和谈进展缓慢，前景令人担忧。他呼吁通过和平谈判推动“早日停火和政治解决”。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="471" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828287?width=700&amp;height=471" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">俄罗斯总统弗拉基米尔·普京三月份在莫斯科克里姆林宫接待了中国国家主席习近平。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Grigory Sysoev/Sputnik</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>耿爽对包括核武器使用在内的战争更广泛风险的详细统计，与3月份北京发表关于解决冲突的12点立场文件后不久，耿爽向联合国所作的陈述形成鲜明对比。在早些时候的演讲中，耿猛烈抨击美国所谓的“恐俄症”。</p><p>在他最新的联合国演讲中，耿爽尽量减少相互指责，而是将重点放在粮食安全等问题上，他曾三度提及这一问题。几天前，普京表示，俄罗斯将退出一项允许<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/great-power-rivalry-looms-over-ukraine-grain-deal-3d2e0eb1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">乌克兰粮食安全通过黑海的</a>协议。中国一直是该产品的最大市场。</p><p>印度智库塔克沙什拉研究所的中国研究研究员马诺吉·科瓦尔拉马尼（Manoj Kewalramani）表示，“根据官方报道，人们得到的感觉是，中国仍然对局势升级和溢出效应感到担忧”。他跟踪北京官员的声明。</p><p>凯瓦尔拉马尼还指出，共产党《人民日报》最近发表的一篇评论表达了对美国利用战争作为借口开辟新战线对抗北京的担忧，例如<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/natos-new-focus-on-china-creates-internal-tension-about-mission-creep-a4a1a77e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">将北大西洋公约组织的授权范围扩大到亚洲</a>。</p><p> “美国试图将乌克兰危机与亚太事务联系起来，威胁欧洲国家与中国‘脱钩’，并施压欧洲国家参与其所谓印太战略，”张健评论道。总部位于北京的智库中国现代国际关系研究院副院长。</p><p>尽管乌克兰双方似乎都不占上风，但长期冲突可能会给中国带来外交和经济影响。尽管北京一直试图将自己定位为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-sticks-close-to-russia-as-it-makes-cautious-diplomatic-push-4416eed8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">和平缔造者</a>，但它有时也会犯错，例如四月份其驻法国最高外交官似乎<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-ambassador-to-france-says-ex-soviet-states-lack-basis-for-sovereignty-8a46ad7d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">对一些前苏联加盟共和国主权的</a>法律基础提出了质疑。现在，外交努力因<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-foreign-minister-qin-gang-replaced-63660fad?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">习近平精心挑选的外交部长</a>秦刚的神秘离职而蒙上阴影。</p><p>习近平在春季调解冲突的努力几乎没有表现出任何后续行动，其中包括派遣外交官前往欧洲推广 2 月份的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/europe-avoids-chinas-belt-and-road-forum-keeping-a-distance-from-xi-and-putin-14f6253b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">12 点立场文件</a>。尽管<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-xi-arrives-in-moscow-as-beijing-seeks-to-position-itself-as-a-peacemaker-8f11d364?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与普京继续进行对话</a>，但习近平尚未​​重复三个月前与乌克兰总统弗拉基米尔·泽连斯基<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-xi-makes-first-call-to-zelensky-since-russian-invasion-b784bb7f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">的一次战时电话交谈</a>。</p><p>由于习近平与普京关系密切<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-pushing-ukraine-cease-fire-gets-cool-reception-in-europe-614774dd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，北京未能让西方官员相信</a>中国在这场冲突中保持中立。皮尤研究中心最新发布的一项调查显示，对习近平和中国的不信任在世界各地普遍存在。调查显示，24 个国家中，71% 的受访者认为中国没有为全球和平与稳定做出贡献。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="427" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828286?width=700&amp;height=427" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">预计中国领导人习近平将于五月在莫斯科派遣中国和平特使李辉出席在沙特阿拉伯举行的乌克兰支持的国际会议。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：马克西姆·希彭科夫/Shutterstock</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>亚洲协会政策研究所高级研究员菲利普·勒科尔表示，一场旷日持久的战争<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economy-barely-grows-as-recovery-fades-5652a92a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">对中国经济</a>、其全球发展目标及其<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/europe-avoids-chinas-belt-and-road-forum-keeping-a-distance-from-xi-and-putin-14f6253b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在欧洲的形象</a>都是不利的，但北京方面尚未明确调整其信息传递。 “没有人对‘十二点和平计划’印象深刻，也没有人对秦刚访问欧洲时印象深刻，”勒科尔说。该计划呼吁停火的批评者表示，其效果将是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-new-poll-89-of-ukrainians-reject-ceding-land-to-reach-peace-with-russia-11656504002?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">将其控制的乌克兰约20%的领土割让给俄罗斯</a>，其中包括莫斯科于2014年吞并的克里米亚。</p><p>美国国务卿安东尼·布林肯（Antony Blinken <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-allies-stick-together-to-confront-russia-and-chinafor-now-76156bf7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">）表示，中国正在采取“平衡行动”</a> ，支持俄罗斯，同时试图将自己塑造成中立参与者和和平力量，“这种压力越来越明显”</p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/xi-jinping-to-meet-blinken-monday-as-u-s-china-resume-high-level-engagement-c898f541?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">六月与习近平会面</a>后不久，他告诉外交关系委员会的理查德·哈斯。<p></p><p>布林肯表示，尽管如此，一旦结束战争的外交有取得成果的现实前景，北京对莫斯科的“一定程度的影响力”可能会有用。</p><p>对中国的欢迎反映了拜登政府重新接触中国的努力，但据十名共和党参议员最近写给布林肯的信称，任何认为北京发挥调解作用会在中国与莫斯科之间产生隔阂的想法都是错误的。他们呼吁阻止北京参与<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-china-meeting-shows-no-breakthrough-to-end-russian-invasion-f71a871d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">任何乌克兰解决方案</a>，称“政府的政策不应允许中国为支持俄罗斯而开脱，也不应允许中国利用这场战争谋取更长期的政治和经济利益。”</p><p>法国智库蒙田研究所的特别顾问弗朗索瓦·戈德门特表示，北京在欧洲作为中立方并不被信任，他对其外交敏锐度表示怀疑，3月份<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-brokered-deal-between-iran-saudi-arabia-marks-a-new-middle-east-d1eaf94e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">中国促成了一项协议</a>，这似乎得到了提振。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-brokered-deal-between-iran-saudi-arabia-marks-a-new-middle-east-d1eaf94e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">沙特阿拉伯与伊朗</a>恢复外交关系。</p><p>戈德门特最近写道：“中国的真正优势在于其他方面：其对各方的商业和技术吸引力大幅增加，以及由此产生的不容忽视的中国作为一个不可避免的合作伙伴，它有能力奖励或惩罚。”</p><p>习近平尚未​​对普京在瓦格纳叛乱期间面临的挑战做出公开反应，但分析人士表示，这可能让他感到不安。政策通讯《GZERO Daily》最近概述了为什么中国领导人可能被迫向莫斯科施压以结束战争：“他正在为普京提供俄罗斯总统无法（或不会）为自己创造的‘出口通道’，”它说。</p><p>习近平对俄罗斯的支持似乎坚定不移，例如，7月份会见了普京的盟友——俄罗斯议会上议院议长瓦伦蒂娜·马特维延科(Valentina Matvienko)——然后几天后<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kerrys-china-trip-restores-talks-on-climate-change-but-falls-short-on-agreement-f89be8e2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">冷落了拜登总统的气候特使</a>约翰·克里(John Kerry)。更悄悄的是，中国7月份还欢迎乌克兰贸易特使塔拉斯·卡奇卡(Taras Kachka)来到北京，并承诺增加中国从乌克兰的进口。</p><p>戈德门特表示，中国的叙述“保留了足够的模糊性，以至于中国共产党事后可以声称他们从未支持普京的战争”。</p><p>北京面临着对其深化与俄罗斯贸易的审查，而此时西方国家正寻求通过将莫斯科<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russias-economy-is-starting-to-come-undone-431a2878?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">排除在全球经济之外</a>并限制其获得武器来进一步惩罚莫斯科入侵乌克兰的行为。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828290?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">中国常驻联合国副代表耿爽上个月强调了粮食安全的必要性，几天前俄罗斯表示将退出允许乌克兰粮食安全通过黑海的协议。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Bianca Otero/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>美国国家情报总监办公室7月份的一份报告称，中国的国有企业<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-aids-russias-war-in-ukraine-trade-data-shows-11675466360?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">向俄罗斯出口</a>船舶导航设备、干扰技术和喷气式战斗机零部件，同时进口能源并为俄罗斯船舶承保保险。报道还援引媒体调查结果称，中国向俄罗斯供应了无人机和半导体。</p><p>但美国情报报告称，中国利用空壳公司、歪曲文件和复杂的供应链，使人们很难了解中国在多大程度上帮助俄罗斯逃避制裁和出口管制。</p><p>在最近为期两周的中国之行中，华盛顿智库战略与国际研究中心的斯科特·肯尼迪没有听到任何结束战争的严肃想法，只听到乌克兰应该接受停火。肯尼迪说，他遇到的一位专家警告说，西方应该明白，俄罗斯可能出于绝望而部署战术核武器。</p><p> “外卖并不令人意外。他们没有批评俄罗斯并建议其清醒过来并撤军，而是将此作为美国和西方停止武装乌克兰的另一个理由。”肯尼迪表示。</p><p>华盛顿智库保卫民主基金会高级研究员克雷格·辛格尔顿表示，瓦格纳叛乱的失败和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-lack-of-weaponry-and-training-risks-stalemate-in-fight-with-russia-f51ecf9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">乌克兰进攻进展有限</a>可能会给中国领导人习近平带来近期的安慰。但他表示，这只是暂时的：“中国著名理论家推测普京可能不再有时间了，习近平现在必须努力应对输掉他发起的与西方的大国冲突。”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> ——劳伦斯·诺曼对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 James T. Areddy： <a href="mailto:James.Areddy@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">James.Areddy@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 02 Aug 2023 16:37:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-drawn-out-ukraine-war-opens-new-risks-for-china-e5fe8b7c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-drawn-out-ukraine-war-opens-new-risks-for-china-e5fe8b7c<author><![CDATA[James T. Areddy]]></author><category>航空航天/国防</category><category>国防设备/产品</category><category>工业品</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>航天</category><category>防御</category><category>国防装备</category><category>产品</category><category>工业品</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Iraq Cracks Down on Dollar Smuggling Amid Growing U.S. Pressure]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>华盛顿旨在阻止美元流向伊朗<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001104282"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828088?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">伊拉克当局正试图破坏由银行、货币交易商和伊朗支持的民兵组成的控制非法货币交易的强大网络。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：murtaja Lateef/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001104282"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/david-s-cloud" itemprop="url" rel="author">大卫·S·克劳德</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name">加桑·阿德南</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 2 日上午 10:51 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/iraq-cracks-down-on-dollar-smuggling-amid-growing-u-s-pressure-8f884e34"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>巴格达—— <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-sanctions-14-iraqi-banks-in-crackdown-on-iran-dollar-trade-33ef9f35?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">随着美国加大压力，</a>阻止美元流入伊朗并更好地将其与世界其他经济体隔离，伊拉克再次试图打击洗钱和走私活动。</p><p> 2003年美国入侵伊拉克后，美元几乎成为伊拉克的第二货币，向该国注入美元以维持其运转。二十年后，伊拉克仍然将其外汇储备存放在纽约联邦储备银行，将其石油出口收益存入其官方账户。</p><p>每天有数亿美元流经监管松散的伊拉克银行和货币兑换商店，美国官员称这些商店充斥着欺诈交易和洗钱活动。他们表示，有强有力的证据表明，这些美元的一部分已经<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/iraq-economy-reels-as-u-s-moves-against-money-flows-to-iran-11674128633?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">跨境进入伊朗，为</a>德黑兰提供了急需的货币，并在一定程度上缓解了美国严厉的制裁。</p><p>另一些则落入伊拉克官员或在该国活动的伊朗支持的民兵或其他中东国家的接收者手中。</p><p>现在，在华盛顿最近采取措施<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/iraqis-fly-to-nearby-countries-to-get-dollars-as-u-s-cracks-down-on-money-laundering-ec366494?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">遏制美元流动给伊拉克总理穆罕默德·苏达尼和经济带来压力之后，伊拉克当局正在扩大对货币交易商的突击</a>搜查，并增加空中和陆地边境检查。</p><p>苏丹尼周二晚间表示，“这是坚持彻底改革金融和银行体系的国家与一群猖獗并努力阻碍改革的走私者和价格操纵者之间的战斗。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="498" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828089?width=700&amp;height=498" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">伊拉克总理穆罕默德·苏达尼表示，该国央行应该对涉嫌洗钱的伊拉克银行采取行动。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：necati savas/Shutterstock</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>美国财政部和纽约联邦储备银行上个月在发现 14 家伊拉克银行从事洗钱和欺诈交易的证据后，禁止这些银行进行美元交易。 11 月份，另外四家伊拉克银行被禁止进行美元交易，当时伊拉克财政部和中央银行也对来自伊拉克的美元电汇实施了更严格的控制。</p><p>美国官员表示，这些举措使伊拉克人更难将资金转移出该国。</p><p>在新措施中，伊拉克政府要求该国央行确保美元交易通过一个新的电子平台进行处理，该平台需要提供有关资金去向的详细信息。</p><p>但伊拉克当局面临着一场艰苦的战斗，破坏由控制非法交易的银行、货币交易商和伊朗支持的民兵组成的强大网络。许多人拥有避免被捕的政治影响力，并且在寻找阻止美元流动的方法方面足智多谋。</p><p>苏丹尼周二承认，伊拉克中央银行应该对涉嫌洗钱的伊拉克银行采取行动，而不是等待美国财政部采取行动。他还指责货币交易员推高伊拉克第纳尔汇率，自美国最新对伊拉克银行实施禁令以来，伊拉克第纳尔汇率已升至1,510第纳尔兑1美元。上个月的汇率为1,470 第纳尔兑1 美元。</p><p>事实上，汇率的上涨凸显了苏丹尼在遵守华盛顿打击美元走私行动时所面临的风险：如果他采取过于激进的行动，可能会激怒伊拉克许多从非法美元贸易中受益的强大利益集团，并推高美元走私的风险。汇率进一步上涨，提高了普通伊拉克人的物价。</p><p>美元走私有多种形式，使工作变得更加复杂。在某些情况下，走私网络从货币交易商处获取美元现金，并用车辆将其运往伊朗、土耳其和其他伊拉克邻国。</p><p>苏丹尼周二发表讲话后不久，伊拉克国家安全部门宣布，在多起洗钱和非法美元交易案件中逮捕了至少 23 人。一位发言人表示，当局在巴格达进行了一系列突袭，捣毁了一个主要的美元走私网络，逮捕了 11 人，并追回了 1,400 万美元现金。</p><p>安全部门发布的一段视频显示，警方在其中一个地点的所谓“安全室”内发现了用收缩包装砖块包装的 100 美元钞票，上面标有“纽约”字样。该发言人表示，被告“承认自己在假贸易公司中充当交易员，以掩护向国外走私货币”。</p><p>在另一起案件中，伊拉克边境当局最近在伊拉克南部与伊朗接壤的过境点逮捕了一名男子，原因是在他的车内发现了 48,300 美元的现金。</p><p>伊拉克银行通过电汇方式将大量美元转移到主要位于迪拜的账户，而迪拜的最终收款人很难追踪。</p><p> “有些银行不遵守规则，”苏丹尼说。 “有些银行只在表面上扮演银行的角色，但实际上却进行转账业务。”</p><p>写信给 David S. Cloud： <a href="mailto:david.cloud@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">david.cloud@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 02 Aug 2023 14:51:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/iraq-cracks-down-on-dollar-smuggling-amid-grinding-us-Pressure-8f884e34</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/iraq-cracks-down-on-dollar-smuggling-amid-grinding-us-Pressure-8f884e34<author><![CDATA[David S. Cloud]]></author><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>洗钱</category><category>金融犯罪</category><category>贩运/走私</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>洗钱</category><category>金融犯罪</category><category>贩卖</category><category>走私</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Russian Drone Strikes Target Ukraine Grain Export Ports, Infrastructure]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>土耳其总统警告普京不要采取导致战争升级的措施<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001103840"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=01DC9687-3E3C-4AD7-84D4-0309F58EB7EF&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Frussian-drone-strikes-target-ukraine-grain-export-ports-infrastructure-5d73dd7b&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">周三早些时候，俄罗斯对乌克兰的粮食储存和港口基础设施发动了一波无人机袭击。俄罗斯7月退出出口协议后，港口城市伊兹梅尔是该国仅存的黑海谷物运输出口之一。照片：乌克兰南方作战司令部/路透社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001103840"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jared-malsin" itemprop="url" rel="author">贾里德·马尔辛</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/laurence-norman" itemprop="url" rel="author">劳伦斯·诺曼</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 2 日上午 7:51 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-drone-strikes-target-ukraine-grain-export-ports-infrastructure-5d73dd7b"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>俄罗斯上个月<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-russia-killed-the-ukraine-grain-deal-faf1f8c5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">退出黑海粮食协议</a>后，俄罗斯对乌克兰港口发动了一波无人机袭击，加剧了对该国粮食出口基础设施的攻击，加剧了人们对这场战争可能再次扰乱世界很大一部分粮食供应的担忧。</p><p>乌克兰官员称，此次袭击使用伊朗制造的 Shahed-136 无人机，袭击了乌克兰南部多瑙河畔伊兹梅尔市及周边地区的粮仓、海运码头和港口行政大楼。俄罗斯上个月退出出口协议后，这座港口城市是该国仅存的黑海谷物运输出口之一。</p><p>乌克兰总检察长办公室表示，袭击损坏了一座谷物升降机、货运码头、生产和仓库设施以及一家航运公司的三层行政办公楼。乌克兰空军表示，在夜间袭击中摧毁了部署在该国南部地区的 11 架无人机，并击落了全国各地的 23 架无人机。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="710" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/c26938bc-3e77-4f72-bf42-84d67b50b249-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>自克里姆林宫选择不延长黑海粮食计划以来，这些袭击加剧了俄罗斯对乌克兰港口和农业基础设施的攻击。这项在联合国和土耳其斡旋下达成的协议使乌克兰去年能够恢复其三个主要港口的出口，从而帮助降低了全球食品价格。</p><p> “世界必须做出回应。当民用港口成为攻击目标时，当恐怖分子故意摧毁甚至是谷物升降机时，这对各大洲的每个人都构成威胁。乌克兰总统弗拉基米尔·泽连斯基周三上午在 Telegram 上表示：“俄罗斯可以而且必须被阻止。”</p><p>自退出协议以来，俄罗斯<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-blames-ukraine-for-fresh-drone-strikes-on-central-moscow-crimea-76556ba7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">对乌克兰港口和粮食码头进行了一系列导弹和无人机袭击</a>，并威胁要袭击黑海的商船。</p><p>对乌克兰多瑙河港口的袭击尤为重要，因为自从俄罗斯对敖德萨市周围更大的港口实施事实上的封锁以来，多瑙河在粮食供应链中变得更加重要。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="525" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828134?width=700&amp;height=525" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">夜间无人机袭击损坏了多瑙河乌克兰港口的这座建筑。</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Ukrainian Emergency Services/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Ukraine uses the Danube route to ship grain on smaller ships, often to Romania, where it is loaded onto larger vessels that take it to the world market. Russia has less capacity to threaten the western Black Sea, which includes the territorial waters of North Atlantic Treaty Organization member Romania, Bulgaria and Turkey.</p><p> The river now accounts for about a quarter of Ukraine&#39;s total exports and US and European officials have sought to support Ukraine&#39;s shipments via the river.</p><p> The strikes along the border of Romania also raise military tensions between Russia and NATO. Russia moved a warship into the southern Black Sea as a part of its <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russias-threats-to-shipping-bring-risk-of-war-to-black-sea-247cbf3a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">broader threats</a> to commercial shipping, the UK Ministry of Defense said last week.</p><p> NATO agreed with Ukraine last week to increase flights by surveillance planes over the Black Sea in response to Russia&#39;s threats.该联盟的一名官员证实，作为该组织加强警惕的一部分，侦察机于 7 月 30 日从土耳其科尼亚市的一个基地起飞，飞越罗马尼亚上空。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828133?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Cargo ships navigate a canal between the Danube River and the Black Sea, in Tulcea, Romania.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Andrei Pugnovschi/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Wheat futures rose 2.7% to $6.70 on Wednesday following the attack, before falling again. Russia&#39;s exit from the deal could eventually drive up grain prices by 10% to 15%, the chief economist of the International Monetary Fund said last month.</p><p> Ukraine accounted for 9% of the world&#39;s exported wheat and nearly <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-shift-on-sunflower-seed-exports-calms-cooking-oil-market-rocked-by-invasion-4839cbc8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">half the world&#39;s supply of sunflower oil</a> before Russia&#39;s invasion and was a key supplier to Europe, the Middle East and Asian countries.</p><p> Last week, a senior European Union official said he believed that by September, Ukraine could use EU routes to export enough grain to replace the amounts it was selling through the Black Sea Grain initiative. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1690" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/670c660e-e0c9-43e9-8c6d-a5cb03e5d9e4-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Since the start of the war, the EU has set up three so-called solidarity lanes to facilitate Ukrainian exports via Europe.迄今为止，已有 4100 万吨粮食、油籽和相关产品通过这些路线离开乌克兰，远高于通过黑海粮食倡议出口的 3300 万吨。</p><p> Wednesday&#39;s attacks came the same day as a highly anticipated phone call between Russian President <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/vladimir-putin">Vladimir Putin</a> and Turkish President Recep</p> Tayyip Erdogan, who helped negotiate the original grain agreement last year and has played a key role in <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/turkeys-double-dealing-in-the-ukraine-war-345dbfdf?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">pressuring Moscow</a> to remain in the deal.<p></p><p> Erdogan warned Putin against taking steps that would escalate the war and said that Turkey would engage in “intense” diplomacy to restart the grain deal, the Turkish president&#39;s office said in a statement after the call.</p><p> Russia&#39;s withdrawal from the deal has strained Putin&#39;s relations with Erdogan, who until recently was one of the only world leaders to hold regular phone conversations with the Russian president. Erdogan <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/turkey-returns-prisoners-to-ukraine-angering-kremlin-688bb3ad?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">shifted his foreign policy toward the West</a> in recent weeks, signaling approval for Sweden&#39;s entrance to NATO and returning a group of Ukrainian military leaders to their country. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="598" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828107?width=700&amp;height=598" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> An inspector surveys the damage at a grain port facility in Izmail, Ukraine.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Prosecutor General&#39;s Office/Reuters</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Western leaders including Secretary of State Antony Blinken have said they are looking to Erdogan to help negotiate a resumption of the grain deal. Wednesday was the first time the Turkish president spoke with Putin since Russia refused to extend the deal on July 17.</p><p> Russia has said it would return to the deal only if Western countries meet its demands, which include reconnecting a Russian agricultural bank to the Swift international payments system and facilitating Russian ammonia exports.</p><p> In addition to Russia&#39;s Danube port attacks, the EU initiative to boost Ukrainian grain exports is also facing political headwinds from within the bloc.</p><p> Poland, which is one of the main routes for Ukrainian grain into the bloc, is threatening to renew a ban on Ukrainian grain entering the country amid protests by farmers who say cheap Ukrainian grain imports are undercutting local producers.</p><p> Poland and several neighboring EU states banned the import of Ukrainian grain in April, sharply cutting the amount of grain Ukraine could send through the EU that month. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828110?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Turkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan speaks at this year&#39;s NATO summit in Vilnius, Lithuania.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Andrey Rudakov/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Poland only lifted the ban after the EU established a temporary mechanism in early May which allowed Ukraine&#39;s grain to transit through Poland, but not to be sold there. That arrangement expires in mid-September and the Polish government is pressing Brussels to extend it.</p><p> Poland&#39;s pressure over Ukraine&#39;s grain exports has sparked a diplomatic row with Ukraine, with Polish officials accusing Kyiv of being ungrateful for the large-scale help Poland has provided Ukraine during the war.</p><p> On Wednesday, Zelensky called for a cooling of tensions between the two countries, warning that politics was undermining the unity between Europe and Ukraine.</p><p> “We greatly appreciate the historical support of Poland, which together with us has become a real shield of Europe from sea to sea. And there cannot be a single crack in this shield,” he tweeted.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Daniel Michaels contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Jared Malsin at <a href="mailto:jared.malsin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jared.malsin@wsj.com</a> and Laurence Norman at <a href="mailto:laurence.norman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">laurence.norman@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 02 Aug 2023 11:51:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-drone-strikes-target-ukraine-grain-export-ports-infrastructure-5d73dd7b</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-drone-strikes-target-ukraine-grain-export-ports-infrastructure-5d73dd7b<author><![CDATA[Jared MalsinLaurence Norman]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>华尔街日报</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>Port/Harbor Operations</category><category> Water Transport/Shipping</category><category>运输/物流</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>港口</category><category>harbor operations</category><category> water transport</category><category>船运</category><category>运输</category><category>后勤</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The West Attacked Russia’s Economy. The Result Is Another Stalemate.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Failure to quickly bring the Russian economy to its knees for its invasion of Ukraine mirrors a larger stalemate on the battlefield <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001101204"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="588" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828104?width=860&amp;height=588" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Economists expect sanctions to cause Russia to stagnate in the years ahead.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Sofya Sandurskaya/tass/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001101204"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/alan-cullison" itemprop="url" rel="author">Alan Cullison</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/georgi-kantchev" itemprop="url" rel="author">Georgi Kantchev</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 2, 2023 7:18 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-west-attacked-russias-economy-the-result-is-another-stalemate-99ec913b"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Weeks after Russia invaded Ukraine last year, a White House official warned Moscow that a raft of US-led sanctions <a href="https://www.cbsnews.com/news/russia-economic-sanctions-ukraine-60-minutes-2022-03-20/" target="_blank" class="icon none">could cut Russia&#39;s economy in half</a> .</p><p> Last week the International Monetary Fund gave some upbeat news for the Kremlin, saying it now expects Russia&#39;s economy to grow 1.5% this year, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-races-to-plug-budget-gap-as-oil-revenues-fall-and-war-costs-rise-6f3c8c5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">supported by extensive state spending</a> . That follows a shrinkage of 2.1% the year before, when Russia became the most sanctioned major economy in the world.</p><p> Economists expect the sanctions to cause Russia <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russias-economy-is-starting-to-come-undone-431a2878?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">to stagnate in the years ahead</a> and the fault lines are already emerging.但西方未能迅速让俄罗斯经济因入侵乌克兰而陷入瘫痪，反映出那里战场上的更大僵局，尽管西方向基辅提供了大量致命援助，并为乌克兰事业提供了经济支持。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="958" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/fc3dc2ca-f48a-4fce-b283-5b5d24676bb8-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> When they were unveiled, Biden administration officials called the sanctions the most consequential in history, and the initial shock and awe roiled Moscow&#39;s financial markets. But today the economy has muddled through <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/putin-promotes-russias-economy-and-hints-again-at-using-nuclear-weapons-6c4368c1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">enough for the Kremlin to support an attritional war</a> that the US had hoped to avoid.</p><p> Sanctions <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/russia-ukraine-latest-news/card/u-s-clamps-export-controls-on-russia-to-limit-access-to-chips-other-technology-uMr2xUjffR4uNEPXLuBR?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">initially starved Russia of microchips</a> and high-tech components last year, crimping its ability to produce precision-guided missiles. But since then Moscow has <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-sanctioned-western-goods-are-still-flowing-into-russia-916db262?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">found loopholes through neighboring countries</a> , and is bombing Ukraine daily with precision weaponry.</p><p> Russia&#39;s crude oil continues to flow, even if the lower prices it fetches have hit state coffers.分析人士表示，制裁的主要影响——技术落后和无法实现现代化——从长远来看将阻碍其经济增长。</p><p> “Sanctions have not destroyed the Russian economy just yet,” said Sergei Guriev, a professor at Sciences Po in Paris and a former Russian government adviser. “They have started to constrain but not stop Putin&#39;s ability to finance this war.”</p><p> Sanctions became an often-used foreign policy tool of the US after it became an economic powerhouse in the previous century. They <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sanctions-will-hurt-russia-but-are-unlikely-to-deter-its-aggression-in-ukraine-11646314400?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">have had a mixed record</a> , often falling short of causing a dramatic change in behavior, particularly in authoritarian states such as Russia, according to analysts who study them. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827608?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Moscow&#39;s quick pivot to Asia from Europe as a trading partner could be to Russia&#39;s advantage.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: maxim shipenkov/epa/Shutterstock</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> How Russia has managed to avoid collapse and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/is-russias-economy-growing-or-shrinking-it-depends-on-the-forecaster-41e7af0c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">eke out some growth</a> within a year despite a Western economic blockade will be a case study for analysts pondering where sanctions make sense as a policy tool in the future.</p><p> Behind Russia&#39;s economic resilience has been a significant government stimulus, a shift to a war economy and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russias-war-on-ukraine-changed-global-oil-trade-here-is-what-it-looks-like-now-11674740567?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">an unprecedented rerouting of its trade to Asian partners</a> , primarily China and India, analysts say.</p><p> The Biden administration defends the sanctions as vital to driving up the price that Russia pays for its war in Ukraine. The latest growth statistics mask the real pain being felt by the economy, a senior administration official said.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> SHARE YOUR THOUGHTS</h4><p> <em>Do you think sanctions against Russia will cause it to rethink its invasion of Ukraine?为什么或者为什么不？ Join the conversation below.</em></p></div></div><p> “We are making Russia&#39;s economy less resilient and less capable of sustaining itself over time,” the official said. “It&#39;s more difficult for them to run their war on Ukraine.”</p><p> Government spending as part of gross domestic product has jumped by 13.5% in the first quarter compared with the same period last year, the highest growth rate in data going back to 1996.</p><p> Economists attribute much of the growth in Russian industrial production this year to weapons and materiel. President <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/vladimir-putin">Vladimir Putin</a> has ordered the government to provide unlimited funding for the war machine.</p><p> The output of “finished metal goods”—a line that analysts say includes weapons and ammunition—rose by 30% in the first half of the year compared with last. Other lines associated with military output have also increased: Production of computers, electronic and optical products also rose by 30%, while the output of special clothing has jumped by 76%. By contrast, auto output is down over 10% year-over-year.</p><p> “What we&#39;re seeing now is a massive boost in demand distribution via military-industrial complex and war beneficiaries, we can call it military Keynesianism,” said Alexandra Prokopenko, a former Russian central-bank official who is now a nonresident scholar at the Berlin-based Carnegie Russia Eurasia Center. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=CC71B144-B6D5-4ADE-B69C-819DC994B692&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fthe-west-attacked-russias-economy-the-result-is-another-stalemate-99ec913b&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Russia launched missile attacks on Odesa early Tuesday hours after quitting an agreement that had ensured the safe passage of Ukraine&#39;s exports through the Black Sea. WSJ&#39;s Matthew Luxmoore reports from the port city. Photo: Igor Tkachenko/Zuma Press<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Continued global demand for Russian commodities has also bolstered the economy. Last year, Russia registered a record current-account surplus, a broad measure of funds flowing into the economy.</p><p> This year, an EU ban on most Russian oil imports has undermined its price. Researchers at Capital Economics expect Russia&#39;s energy export revenues to decline from $340 billion in 2022 to $200 billion this year and stabilize at around that level in 2024.</p><p> At the same time, Russian oil production has declined only slightly. That is because Moscow has <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-uses-little-known-traders-to-sell-oil-to-the-world-4bb538cd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">found ways to sell its oil</a> to Asia by <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-will-rely-on-shadow-tanker-fleet-to-keep-oil-flowing-11670036535?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">creating a shadow fleet</a> of tankers owned, insured and chartered outside the West. In recent weeks, that has also helped <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-defies-sanctions-by-selling-oil-above-price-cap-bae1c271?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">reduce the discount that Russian oil sells at</a> relative to global benchmarks.</p><p> “Russia continues to sell to nonmembers of the sanctioning coalition and, in that sense, the impact of the oil sanctions, while substantial, is still not decisive,” Guriev said.</p><p> In the US, officials say that for sanctions to be effective, governments must enforce them constantly and halt workarounds as the Russians find them. The EU has recently taken action to enforce sanctions harder, potentially choking off some of the evasion routes.</p><p> Russia&#39;s homegrown drive for import substitution has shown mixed results so far. Some 65% of industrial enterprises in Russia are dependent on imported equipment, according to a poll by Moscow&#39;s Higher School of Economics published in June. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="473" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827639?width=700&amp;height=473" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Russia&#39;s crude oil continues to flow, but the lower prices it fetches have hit state coffers.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: ALEXANDER MANZYUK/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Nicholas Mulder, a professor of history at Cornell University who has specialized in sanctions, said the West&#39;s attempt to sanction a country as large as Russia could emerge as a cautionary tale in the long run. Russia&#39;s sheer size makes it impossible to cut it off from the world economy, he said. It remains a major source of raw materials for advanced economies, while for the developing world it is a crucial supplier of food and fertilizer.</p><p> Moscow&#39;s quick pivot to Asia from Europe as a trading partner could be to Russia&#39;s advantage, he said. “Russia has in fact hitched itself to the fastest-growing region in the world,” said Mulder, noting that three-quarters of global economic growth <strong>&nbsp;</strong> this year will be in Asia. “Without Asia&#39;s cooperation, you can&#39;t cripple Russia&#39;s economy.”</p><p> Mulder believes Russia&#39;s weak point is <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russias-big-economic-problem-not-enough-workers-d5164d47?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a growing shortage of labor</a> , the one resource that Moscow can&#39;t replace with a trade reshuffle. Russia is suffering its worst deficit since the 1990s as emigration and wartime mobilization sap workers from companies—a trend only expected to worsen due to the country&#39;s poor demographic outlook.</p><p> Last month, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-raises-rates-as-ukraine-war-costs-mount-a41bfa23?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Russia&#39;s central bank raised interest rates</a> by a larger-than-expected 1%, with more increases expected later this year, and it signaled that the labor shortage was fueling inflation.</p><p> “Labor market crunch, bubbling inflation, the impact of technology sanctions—these things matter and they matter a lot,” Guriev said. “They slow down Russian economic growth, its ability to innovate and upgrade itself. Russia will stagnate and its capacity to catch up with developed countries will be limited.”</p><p> Prokopenko said that while state spending on the war is currently boosting the economy, “that&#39;s not productive growth.”</p><p> “The Russian economy is not sustainable in the long term. It all reminds of the Soviet times and we know how the Soviet economy went,” she said.</p><p> Write to Alan Cullison at <a href="mailto:alan.cullison@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">alan.cullison@wsj.com</a> and Georgi Kantchev at <a href="mailto:georgi.kantchev@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">georgi.kantchev@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828109?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Russia is suffering its worst deficit since the 1990s as emigration and wartime mobilization sap workers from companies.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Dmitry Serebryakov/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 02 Aug 2023 11:18:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-west-attacked-russias-economy-the-result-is-another-stalemate-99ec913b</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-west-attacked-russias-economy-the-result-is-another-stalemate-99ec913b<author><![CDATA[Alan CullisonGeorgi Kantchev]]></author><category> wsjfinance-eur</category><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>Output/Production</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>产品与服务</category><category>Economic Performance/Indicators</category><category> Economic Growth/Recession</category><category> Trade/External Payments</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>国际关系</category><category>International Sanctions</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>Trade Barriers/Restrictions</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>输出</category><category>生产</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>产品</category><category>服务</category><category>economic performance</category><category> indicators</category><category> economic growth</category><category> recession</category><category> trade</category><category> external payments</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>国际关系</category><category>international sanctions</category><category>政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>trade barriers</category><category> restrictions</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘How Do I Do That?’ The New Hires of 2023 Are Unprepared for Work]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Remote learning during the pandemic left students short of basic skills. Now companies are trying to teach them on the job. <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827972/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="密歇根州大急流城约翰·鲍尔动物园的售票处。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> The ticket office of the John Ball Zoo in Grand Rapids, Mich. Steve Koss for The Wall Street Journal <span>Steve Koss for The Wall Street Journal</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001101284"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001101284"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/douglas-belkin" itemprop="url" rel="author">Douglas Belkin</a></span> , <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ben-chapman" itemprop="url" rel="author">Ben Chapman</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ben-kesling" itemprop="url" rel="author">Ben Kesling</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 2, 2023 5:30 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/lost-learning-remote-pandemic-workplace-skills-new-employees-51351b33"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Roman Devengenzo was consulting for a robotics company in Silicon Valley last fall when he asked a newly minted mechanical engineer to design a small aluminum part that could be fabricated on a lathe—a skill normally mastered in the first or second year of college.</p><p> “How do I do that?” asked the young man.</p><p> So Devengenzo, an engineer who has built technology for NASA and Google, and who charges consulting clients a minimum of $300 an hour, spent the next three hours teaching Lathework 101. “You learn by doing,” he said. “These kids in school during the pandemic, all they&#39;ve done is work on computers.”</p><p>疫情期间多年的远程学习所产生的连锁反应正在使全国各地的工作场所陷入困境。这是专业服务职位空缺和商品无法进入市场的原因之一。 It also helps explain why national productivity has fallen for the past five quarters, the longest contraction since at least 1948, according to the US Labor Department.</p><p> The shortcomings run the gamut from general knowledge, including how to make change at a register, to soft skills such as working with others. Employers are spending more time and resources searching for candidates and often lowering expectations when they hire.然后，他们花费数百万美元来解决新员工缺乏基本技能的问题。</p><p>位于密歇根州大急流城的一个以企业为主导的劳动力发展组织 Talent First 正在鼓励雇主停止尝试根据技能进行招聘。相反，招聘经理应该寻找学习的意愿，总裁凯文·斯托茨说。</p><p> “雇主们说，‘我们只是想找到一些能让镜子起雾的人，’”斯托茨说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="700" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828009?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>自2020年疫情爆发、远程学习让学生走出学校进入虚拟教室以来，工程师、上班族、士兵和护士参加的国家认证和评估考试的通过率均有所下降。</p><p> Among the approximately 40,000 candidates taking the Fundamentals of Engineering exam for work as professional engineers, scores fell by about 10% during the pandemic, said David Cox, CEO of the National Council of Examiners for Engineering and Surveying.</p><p> That means fewer engineers on the job and a lower degree of competency among those who make it, he said.</p><p> The sharpest declines in scores came on questions measuring the most specialized knowledge. Structural engineers failed to answer questions about the use of trusses in the construction of bridges and roadways, Cox said.</p><p> “These are areas that are very much involved in public safety,” he said.</p><p> Students in elementary and middle schools across the nation fell behind by an average of about four months during the pandemic after classes switched to remote learning in 2019 and stayed that way in some cases through 2021. On national <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/education-departments-first-pandemic-era-trend-data-show-worst-reading-math-declines-in-decades-11662004860?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">standardized tests</a> , the scores of fourth- and eighth-graders fell to 30-year lows.</p><p> Students who were in high-school and college when Covid-19 hit and are now entering the workforce didn&#39;t fare much better. Despite lowered standards at many schools during the pandemic, <a href="https://www.chalkbeat.org/2022/1/24/22895461/2021-graduation-rates-decrease-pandemic" target="_blank" class="icon none">high-school graduation rates fell</a> . Scores for college admissions exams dropped <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/act-test-scores-drop-to-lowest-levels-in-more-than-30-years-11665593614?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">to the lowest level in three decades</a> .</p><p> Janet Godwin, chief executive of ACT, the nonprofit organization which administers the college admission test of the same name, said more high-school graduates today lack the fundamental academic skills needed for college and the workplace, with low-performing students facing the steepest declines.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> SHARE YOUR THOUGHTS</h4><p> <em>In what ways have people in your workplace needed extra support and skill-building since the pandemic? Join the conversation below.</em></p></div></div><p> In Covid-19&#39;s aftermath, many college professors restructured curricula for students who lack basic study skills.</p><p> “Reading, writing and critical-thinking skills are not the same as they were in the past,” said Mike Altman, a religion professor at the University of Alabama who said he has narrowed his curriculum to give his students more time to master basics.</p><p> During the pandemic more than 100,000 nurses left the field, <a href="https://www.healthaffairs.org/do/10.1377/forefront.20220412.311784/" target="_blank" class="icon none">the largest decline in four decades of available data,</a> a study in the journal Health Affairs showed. That has placed tremendous strain on hospitals and increased demands on programs to graduate more nurses. But students taking entrance exams to study nursing are scoring an average of about 5 percentage points lower than before the pandemic, limiting the number of students eligible to enroll in nursing programs. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=839822A9-3A5F-4A5D-9390-E94EDF4A2336&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Flost-learning-remote-pandemic-workplace-skills-new-employees-51351b33&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">人工智能在白领工作中发挥着越来越重要的作用，能够起草电子邮件、演示文稿、图像等。工人们已经因为科技而失去了工作，一些首席执行官正在改变未来的招聘计划。 《华尔街日报》解释道。插图：雅各布·雷诺兹<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>More students who do enroll struggle to earn passing grades, said Patty Knecht, Vice President of Ascend Learning Healthcare, a private company which helps train medical professionals. And even if they do graduate, more are struggling to pass a certification exam. By then, they may already be on the payroll but unable to work. The delays cost hospitals an average of $42,000 per student who fails the certification exam, said Knecht.</p><p> Last year, Ivy Tech Community College, the largest nursing program in Indiana, embedded tutors in classrooms to assist lagging students with skills they should have mastered in high school. Some of the most basic included the math necessary to figure out correct dosages for medicine.</p><p> Joseph Mulumba, who is about to start his sophomore year in the Ivy Tech nursing program, was a high-school sophomore in Indiana when the pandemic arrived. His school was remote for a year.</p><p> “I feel like I would have learned a lot more if not for the pandemic, “ Mulumba said. “When I got here I realized I wasn&#39;t ready for nursing school. I realized I didn&#39;t know how to study.”</p><p> Jerrica Moses, national recruitment manager for Senture, a London, Ky.-based call-center company, says new workers have problems with soft skills, such as an inability to deal with frustration. Senture, which employs about 4,200 customer-service representatives, has adopted a new set of tests to determine which prospective employees will be able to keep their cool under stress from angry or rude callers.</p><p> “Candidates who wash out respond by explaining how aggravated they get with the callers and then focus on the stress,” said Moses. Most of the people who struggle are under 25 years old, she added. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="842" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827911?width=1260&amp;height=842" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Ivan Schury, 17, helps cook on the line at the John Ball Zoo&#39;s Monkey Island Cafe.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Steve Koss for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In Grand Rapids, managers at the John Ball Zoo are coaching seasonal workers in their teens and early 20s on basics such as why it&#39;s important to look visitors in the eye, and how to make change at a cash register.</p><p> They are also trying to instill a work ethic in their employees that includes taking some initiative, getting off their phones and engaging with visitors, said Laura Davis, the director of strategy and organizational development at the zoo. Her young employees haven&#39;t been held accountable for things like finishing homework assignments, and Davis believes that has led to a decline in motivation.</p><p> “They&#39;re not looking to be productive,” Davis said. “If they&#39;re not told what to do, if someone isn&#39;t managing every second and keeping them busy, their inclination is not to self identify what they can do—it&#39;s to do nothing.”</p><p> The pandemic arrived when Ivan Schury was in the eighth grade. Now 17 years old and a supervisor in the zoo&#39;s kitchen, he said the isolation he and his peers experienced over the next few years have left many distracted and disengaged.</p><p> Last week a teenager working the fry station kept wandering off. “He just kept walking away to talk to his friends at the counter,” Schury said. “I spend a lot of time making sure people stay on task.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827910?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Charity Fields, age 19, stands inside the gift shop of the John Ball Zoo.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Steve Koss for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Charity Fields, 19 years old, works in the gift shop and says she is frequently surprised by the lack of motivation of her younger co-workers. A few days ago a 16-year-old fellow sales associate sat in a chair reading a book while customers shopped.</p><p> “I told her we weren&#39;t really supposed to do that,” Fields said. The girl got up, stood near the cash register, leaned on the counter and continued to read.</p><p> The problem extends to the US military, exacerbating <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/military-recruiting-crisis-veterans-dont-want-their-children-to-join-510e1a25?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">pressures the services face from poor recruiting</a> .</p><p> Army recruits aren&#39;t communicating within their squads as well as they did before  the pandemic, instructors say. Scores on recruiting exams fell 9% since the pandemic and prompted the Army to create a new testing boot camp to help recruits pass, a requirement for gaining admission to the military.</p><p> Army Secretary Christine Wormuth believes a lot of the struggles are tied into isolation that took root when students learned remotely during the pandemic.</p><p> “So many young people spent two years in relative isolation and not doing a lot of group projects,” she said.</p><p> Young workers&#39; struggles have become vividly apparent to Criteria Corp, a Los Angeles company that administers about 10 million assessments a year to evaluate prospective employees. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827523?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> New soldiers at Ft. Moore in Georgia are drilled in test-taking skills, including deep-breathing exercises, so they can perform better on the Armed Services Vocational Aptitude Battery, or ASVAB.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: David Walter Banks for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Results for test takers overall have held steady with a notable decline in the scores of men between 18 and 24 and usually with a high-school education, said Josh Millet, co-founder and CEO of the company.</p><p> The company&#39;s Criteria Basic Skills Test measures reading comprehension, verbal skills and numeracy. Companies use it to hire for positions such as administrative assistants, customer-service representatives, medical assistants, insurance salespeople and bank tellers. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> Men under 25 struggled with the verbal section of this standardized test</h4><p> <em>Which of the following sentences contains an error?</em></p><p> A. Halfway there, they ran out of fuel.</p><p> B. They began practice their piano duet.</p><p> C. This book is about sea creatures.</p><p> D. His business partner agreed to meet with him.</p><p> <em>Choose the word that completes the sentence correctly.</em></p><p> Denise thought working with a reporter would be exciting, but she had answered the same question several times and was beginning to find the interview_________.</p><p> A. unique</p><p> B. repugnant</p><p> C. exhilarating</p><p> D. tedious</p><p> E. satisfying</p><p> Source: Criteria Basic Skills Test</p></div></div><p> Verbal scores for men under 25 declined by 11 percentage points over the three years of the pandemic. Scores for women were less dramatically affected. The biggest dips among men were registered in communication skills, reading comprehension, grammar, spelling and attention to detail, said Millet.</p><p> “Our customers consistently tell us that finding high-quality candidates is the single greatest challenge to the successful execution of their talent strategies, and it seems that diminished educational outcomes may exacerbate that challenge,” Millet said.</p><p> Cindy Neal, owner of Express Employment Professionals in Peoria, Ill., places about 1,500 people in jobs every year. Since the pandemic, she has seen sharp declines in the behavior of job applicants as well as their performance on employment exams.</p><p> The company has long offered courses for people to gain new skills such as QuickBooks. This spring they added new courses to help prospective workers with soft skills. Some of the chapters taught include taking initiative, personal productivity, cellphone etiquette, workplace hygiene, dressing appropriately for work and handling conflict with co-workers.</p><p> “This stuff used to be taught in schools,” Neal said. “Now people have to be told not to bring their kids to work.”</p><p> Results on the 15-minute employment exam the company administers to clients when they walk in the door are also declining.</p><p> Tasks on the quiz include recognizing misspellings in words like “availability,” “repetition” and “privilege,” and math questions such as: “If you were asked to load 225 boxes onto a truck and the boxes are crated, with each crate containing nine boxes, how many crates would you need to load?”</p><p> The scores in math and spelling are the worst she&#39;s seen in 30 years, she said, adding, “I&#39;m really concerned by the product that&#39;s coming out of the school system currently.”</p><p> Write to Douglas Belkin at <a href="mailto:Doug.Belkin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Doug.Belkin@wsj.com</a> , Ben Chapman at <a href="mailto:ben.chapman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ben.chapman@wsj.com</a> and Ben Kesling at <a href="mailto:ben.kesling@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ben.kesling@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 02 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/lost-learning-remote-pandemic-workplace-skills-new-employees-51351b33</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/lost-learning-remote-pandemic-workplace-skills-new-employees-51351b33<author><![CDATA[Douglas BelkinBen ChapmanBen Kesling]]></author><category> photo-commission</category><category>领导者</category><category>wsj-usnews</category><category>劳工/人事</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>招聘</category><category>Work-Life Balance</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>教育</category><category>健康</category><category>General Labor Issues</category><category> Living/Lifestyle</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>Outbreaks/Epidemics</category><category> School</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>Telecommuting</category><category>大学学院</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Career Education</category><category>劳动</category><category>人员</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>recruitment</category><category> work-life balance</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>教育</category><category>健康</category><category>general labor issues</category><category> living</category><category>生活方式</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>outbreaks</category><category>流行病</category><category>学校</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>telecommuting</category><category>大学</category><category>大学</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>career education </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Toyota’s Land Cruiser to Return to U.S.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Carmaker announces new version of off-roading SUV that aims to compete with Jeep and Ford Bronco <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001103297"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828039?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Toyota&#39;s new Land Cruiser made its debut in Tokyo, and could be back in North America next year.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Akio Kon/Bloomberg News </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001103297"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/river-davis" itemprop="url" rel="author">River Davis</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated Aug. 2, 2023 4:27 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/toyotas-land-cruiser-to-return-to-the-u-s-7b2eb343"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p><br> TOKYO— <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TM" class="company-name">Toyota</a> Motor is bringing a long-running icon of off-roading back to the US</p><p> At an event in Tokyo on Wednesday, Toyota showed off a new Land Cruiser, reminiscent of boxy pre-2000s versions of the sport-utility vehicle. The company said it plans to bring the new vehicle to the US next year, two years after discontinuing the Land Cruiser in that market.</p><p> The move resembles <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ford-to-reveal-new-bronco-after-24-years-off-the-market-11594667167" target="_blank" class="icon none">Ford&#39;s decision in 2020 to relaunch</a> its previously discontinued off-roading SUV, the Bronco.</p><p> Like the Bronco, the new Land Cruiser could put <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/jeep-looks-to-veer-out-of-sales-ditch-74ba0a58?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">further pressure</a> on rival Jeep&#39;s position in the “adventure vehicle” category. Car companies in recent years have been <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/suvs-are-bumper-to-bumper-on-dealer-lots-with-more-on-the-way-11562491801?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">crowding showrooms</a> with new versions of SUVs and other big, higher-profit vehicles. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827261?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> The Land Cruiser discontinued in the US in 2021 hadn&#39;t received a major update in years. Starting at upward of $80,000, it struggled to compete in the high-price segment, though it retained a following among some off-road enthusiasts.</p><p> The US price of the new Land Cruiser will start in the mid-$50,000s.</p><p> Toyota is marketing the new model as an SUV for people who actually drive off-road, rather than just daydreaming about it. “At the heart of this is reliability and durability and performance over rough terrain,” said Chief Branding Officer Simon Humphries. He called it “proud to be raw and utilitarian.”</p><p> Humphries said the company welcomes competition from off-roading-SUV rivals. “It&#39;s like a sports car—there are Land Cruiser guys and there are Bronco guys. Everyone has their own preference,” he said.</p><p> The new Land Cruiser will go on sale next year in the US as a hybrid vehicle, underscoring Toyota&#39;s resolve to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/toyota-pitches-a-new-prius-as-plug-in-hybrids-battle-evs-for-share-31785660?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">continue making gasoline-electric cars</a> even as more customers choose fully battery-powered models.</p><p> Toyota introduced the Land Cruiser in the 1950s for what was then known as Japan&#39;s National Police Reserve, a predecessor to today&#39;s Ground Self Defense Force—that is, the army. Its name was a nod to Britain&#39;s Land Rover.</p><p> Through the years, the Land Cruiser became popular in places with rough terrain such as Australia and the Middle East. Icelandic glaciers, Australian underground mines and other locales with extreme conditions are a staple of Toyota promotions. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828040?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Toyota&#39;s chief branding officer, Simon Humphries, said the new Land Cruiser is &#39;proud to be raw and utilitarian.&#39;</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Akio Kon/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The company said that as of June 2023 it had sold 11.3 million Land Cruiser models globally over the years.</p><p> Its moment in the sun in the US came around the turn of the century, when Americans were buying more than 15,000 Land Cruisers annually. By the time it was discontinued in 2021, annual sales had dwindled to just a few thousand units, less than 1% of sales of Toyota&#39;s RAV4 SUV.</p><p> The new Land Cruiser has high-mounted headlights and a simple, angular structure. Humphries said the design had evolved naturally in a direction that recalled older models because the priority was functionality. Some recent Land Cruiser models had aimed for more of a luxury feel.</p><p> Write to River Davis at <a href="mailto:river.davis@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">river.davis@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 02 Aug 2023 08:27:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/toyotas-land-cruiser-to-return-to-the-us-7b2eb343</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/toyotas-land-cruiser-to-return-to-the-us-7b2eb343<author><![CDATA[River Davis]]></author><category>机动车</category><category>Passenger Cars</category><category> Sports Utility Vehicles</category><category>汽车</category><category>New Products/Services</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>产品与服务</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Toyota Motor</category><category> 7203.TO</category><category> JP:7203</category><category> new products</category><category>服务</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>产品</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>机动车</category><category>passenger cars</category><category> sports utility vehicles</category><category>汽车</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Taiwan Unveils Dates for U.S. Stops by Vice President Despite China’s Protests]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>赖清德将于8月12日抵达纽约，前往巴拉圭，并于8月16日经旧金山返回<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001103582"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="603" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828065?width=860&amp;height=603" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">台湾副总统赖清德的访问计划引起了北京方面异常强烈的反应。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：ChiangYing-ying/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001103582"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/joyu-wang" itemprop="url" rel="author">王乔宇</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 2 日凌晨 2:27 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/taiwan-unveils-dates-for-u-s-stops-by-vice-president-despite-chinas-protests-17106008"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> TAIPEI—Taiwan Vice President Lai Ching-te plans to stop in New York and San Francisco this month on his way to and from a formal visit to Paraguay, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/taiwans-vice-president-plans-stop-in-the-u-s-at-a-delicate-moment-886e484b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">defying Chinese warnings</a> .</p><p>亚历山大·尤伊·塔赫 (Alexander Yui Tah) 表示，赖清德计划于 8 月 12 日抵达纽约，并于第二天晚上启程前往巴拉圭，这是他为期 7 天的行程的一部分，他将出席巴拉圭即将上任的总统圣地亚哥·佩尼亚·帕拉西奥斯 (Santiago Peña Palacios) 于 8 月 15 日举行的就职典礼。 -雷，台湾外交部副部长。</p><p> Yui周三在台北举行的新闻发布会上表示，他将于8月16日下午抵达旧金山，并于第二天飞回台湾。</p><p>台湾官员在美国的停留（正式称为过境）是华盛顿和台北之间精心安排的一部分，目的是允许台湾领导人在两国于 1979 年断绝正式外交关系后在美国领土上与对方接触。双方长期以来一直坚持对中途停留的样板解释，他们说这些中途停留的安排通常是基于“安全、舒适、便利和尊严的原则”。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=660B6D5E-1625-4388-9BA2-82874CFBAE59&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Ftaiwan-unveils-dates-for-u-s-stops-by-vice-president-despite-chinas-protests-17106008&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Taiwan&#39;s annual military exercises and civilian drills have expanded dramatically this year in the wake of the Ukraine war and increasing fears of invasion from mainland China. WSJ visited the island democracy to see how it is preparing to defend itself. Photo: Joyu Wang<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>这位台湾副总统的访问计划于七月份首次宣布，但引发了北京方面异常强烈的反应，北京对<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-taiwan-relations-tensions-explained-11653322751?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">近年来美台关系的升温</a>感到不安。中国共产党认为台湾是中国的一部分，尽管它从未统治过台湾，并反对华盛顿与台北之间的任何官方沟通。</p><p>中国外交部发言人表示，北京已向华盛顿提出强烈抗议，并重申台湾是中美关系中绝对红线的立场。</p><p> Washington “should stop sending erroneous signals to the &#39;Taiwan independence&#39; separatist forces,” spokeswoman Mao Ning said during a regular press conference in Beijing on July 17, when Taipei announced the trip.</p><p>中国新任驻美国大使谢锋后来在阿斯彭安全论坛上对观众表示，北京的首要任务是阻止赖清德访问美国，“这就像一头灰犀牛向我们冲来”。</p><p>明年初举行的台湾总统选举中，执政党候选人赖智是目前接替蔡英文总统的领跑者</p>-文。他曾多次提出被北京视为支持独立的立场，不过黎智英表示，如果当选，他不会寻求<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/taiwan-opposition-taps-popular-former-cop-in-election-thats-pivotal-for-u-s-china-b59f81bd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">改变现状</a>。<p></p><p>在回答有关中方言论的问题时，由伊重申此类过境是例行公事，并表示赖清德此行“不应成为引起对方不适的借口，也不应以此为借口加深冲突。” ”</p><p>台湾外交部在 7 月 20 日的一份声明中嘲笑了谢的言论，称这位中国外交官对犀牛的评论“玷污了无辜动物的形象”。</p><p> Yui 表示，黎智英行程中的美国站仍在计划中，并补充说，他在纽约和旧金山停留的详细信息将在最终确定后公布。</p><p>巴拉圭是台湾仅存的少数官方外交盟友之一，也是南美洲唯一的一个。今年早些时候，蔡英文访问了危地马拉和伯利兹的外交伙伴。</p><p>在春季访问期间，她在加利福尼亚州会见了众议院议长凯文·麦卡锡（加利福尼亚州共和党），这是台湾领导人在美国领土上举行的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-warnings-loom-over-speaker-mccarthys-meeting-with-taiwans-leader-ca4e8062?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">最高级别政治会议</a>。蔡英文返回台湾后不久，中国在台湾周边展开了为期数天的实弹演习。</p><p>写信给 Joyu Wang： <a href="mailto:joyu.wang@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">joyu.wang@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 02 Aug 2023 06:27:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/taiwan-unveils-dates-for-us-stops-by-vice-president-despite-chinas-protests-17106008</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/taiwan-unveils-dates-for-us-stops-by-vice-president-despite-chinas-protests-17106008<author><![CDATA[Joyu Wang]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Trump Is Indicted in Federal Probe of His Efforts to Reverse 2020 Election]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Grand jury levels new charges at former president stemming from special counsel&#39;s investigation <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001102536"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=CE411241-E264-44EF-BA23-411C000BCB69&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Ftrump-indictment-jack-smith-2020-election-4b351abf&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> A federal grand jury in Washington has indicted former President Donald Trump in connection with his efforts to overturn the 2020 presidential election results. Trump has denied wrongdoing and accused prosecutors of pursuing him for political reasons. Photo: Jeff Swensen/Getty Images<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001102536"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sadie-gurman" itemprop="url" rel="author">Sadie Gurman</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/aruna-viswanatha" itemprop="url" rel="author">Aruna Viswanatha</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated Aug. 1, 2023 9:46 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-indictment-jack-smith-2020-election-4b351abf"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> WASHINGTON— <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">Donald Trump</a> was indicted Tuesday in an unprecedented criminal case accusing the former president of trying to subvert the will of American voters through <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-jack-smith-jan-6-letter-classified-documents-hearing-e679b87?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">his attempts to cling to power</a> after he lost the 2020 election.</p><p> The <a href="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/documents/trumpindictment080123.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">indictment</a> by a federal grand jury in Washington, DC <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-new-charges-facing-donald-trump-and-how-he-might-defend-himself-53a2b45?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">charges Trump with four crimes</a> , including conspiring to defraud the US, obstructing an official proceeding, and conspiring against the rights of voters for his actions that culminated in the Jan. 6, 2021, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-protesters-are-in-the-building-inside-the-capitol-stormed-by-a-pro-trump-mob-11609984654?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">attack by his supporters on the US Capitol</a> . The indictment charges Trump alone, but describes <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/six-co-conspirators-described-in-trumps-2020-election-indictment-1475445d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">six co-conspirators</a> working with him, including people identifiable as Rudy Giuliani and several other lawyers who worked with him to contest the 2020 election results.</p><p> Many of the details referenced in the case have been previously revealed, including from a House panel that investigated the attack. But the 45-page document <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-most-notable-passages-in-the-dojs-indictment-of-trump-9dd1688d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">paints a detailed portrait</a> of Trump&#39;s alleged efforts to press claims that the election had been marred by fraud, even though he had been told repeatedly they had no merit, and how he leaned on officials in battleground states he had lost including Arizona, Georgia and Michigan to support his efforts.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> After those initial efforts failed, the indictment alleges, Trump pushed his own Justice Department to falsely claim election fraud, and pressed Vice President <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/mike-pence">Mike Pence</a> to overturn the results, telling Pence at one point: “You&#39;re too honest.” He then called his supporters to Washington and urged them to “fight like hell” just before they marched to the Capitol on Jan. 6.</p><p> Brought by special counsel Jack Smith, the indictment <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-trump-indictment-adds-fresh-uncertainty-to-2024-presidential-race-179d979a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">opens a second federal criminal case</a> against Trump under the administration led by President Biden, who beat him in the 2020 race for the White House and is now his potential opponent next year, with <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/whos-running-for-president-in-2024-adb754e2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Trump the GOP front-runner</a> for 2024.</p><p> Trump is scheduled to appear in federal court in Washington, DC on Thursday. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822835?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Then-President Donald Trump speaking to supporters near the White House on Jan. 6, 2021, before the attack on the Capitol.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Brendan Smialowski/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The statutes carry maximum penalties. Attempting to obstruct an official proceeding, for example, carries a maximum sentence of 20 years in prison. But defendants rarely face such sentences.</p><p> In a brief appearance where he took no questions, Smith called the Capitol attack “an unprecedented assault on the seat of American democracy. As described in the indictment, it was fueled by lies.”</p><p> Despite losing, Trump spread lies that there had been fraud in the election, and that he had actually won, the indictment alleges. “Each of these conspiracies…targeted a bedrock function of the United States federal government: the nation&#39;s process of collecting, counting, and certifying the results of the presidential election,” prosecutors assert in the indictment.</p><p> In a social media post, Trump said the case was a “pathetic attempt” by the Justice Department to “interfere with the 2024 Presidential Election.”</p><p> Within minutes, the Trump campaign sent a fundraising email, portraying him as a victim of political persecution. “It&#39;s not just my freedom on the line, but yours as well—and I will NEVER let them take it from you,” it read.</p><p> In the indictment, prosecutors acknowledged that Trump had a right to challenge the election results and even falsely claim fraud. But they said what he did went far beyond such rights and involved discounting legitimate votes.</p><p> The indictment adds to the cloud of legal challenges. Smith&#39;s office also is prosecuting Trump on separate charges that he <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-indicted-in-document-case-b4e563d7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">improperly retained classified government documents</a> at his Mar-a-Lago resort and obstructed the government&#39;s efforts to retrieve them. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1030" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/8864d3c0-3c35-44e3-9577-c9feff236e8f-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> The district attorney in Fulton County, Ga., <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/georgia-supreme-court-denies-trump-motion-to-block-election-interference-investigation-700d1719?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">also has been investigating Trump for election interference</a> . He awaits trial on 34 felony charges brought by local prosecutors in New York in a business-records case stemming from <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/grand-jury-votes-to-indict-donald-trump-a9512240?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a hush-money payment made to a porn star</a> in the final stretch of the 2016 election.</p><p> Trump has denied wrongdoing in the federal, New York and Georgia matters, and accused prosecutors of pursuing him for political reasons.</p><p> Prosecutors <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/jan-6-capitol-attack-the-rioters-legal-reckoning-visualized-af640d5c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">have charged more than 1,000 people</a> in connection with the riot, for crimes ranging from trespassing to assault and obstructing the Congressional proceeding, almost all of whom were at the Capitol during the violence. More than 500 have pleaded guilty, and several who were convicted of playing a leading role in the violence <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/oath-keepers-member-gets-more-than-eight-years-for-role-in-jan-6-riot-e72c3347?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">have been sentenced to years in prison</a> . Trump is among the first who didn&#39;t directly participate in the riot to face federal charges in connection with the attack.</p><p> The Jan. 6 Capitol attack led to Trump&#39;s unprecedented second impeachment a week before he left office, with the Democratic House alleging that Trump incited an insurrection. He was later acquitted in the Senate.</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> The probe has advanced for months on several tracks, with prosecutors examining efforts that included assembling fake slates of electors to send to Congress; pressuring Pence to thwart the congressional certification of Biden&#39;s win; pressing state officials to undo their results; fundraising with false claims of election fraud; and rallying his supporters to march to the Capitol.</p><p> Federal grand jurors in Washington have heard from witnesses including election officials from several states, former White House lawyers and a list of Trump&#39;s closest aides. Pence, Trump&#39;s former chief of staff Mark Meadows and other senior officials in <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mike-pence-testifies-before-jan-6-grand-jury-investigating-donald-trump-6318d359?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Trump&#39;s closest circles</a> also testified after Trump&#39;s lawyers unsuccessfully tried to block their appearances, citing executive privilege. Prosecutors interviewed Trump&#39;s former personal lawyer Giuliani for eight hours.</p><p> The co-conspirators are unnamed, though the descriptions in the document indicate that they are Giuliani, Trump lawyers John Eastman, Sidney Powell and Kenneth Chesebro and former Justice Department official Jeffrey Clark. A sixth is described as a political consultant, whose identity is unclear.</p><p> The six, while unindicted, could potentially face charges as Smith&#39;s investigation is ongoing.</p><p> “Every fact Mayor Rudy Giuliani possesses about this case establishes the good-faith basis President Donald Trump had for the actions he took during the two-month period charged in the indictment,” his political adviser, Ted Goodman, said.</p><p> Eastman&#39;s lawyer, Charles Burnham, said the indictment was a misleading attempt to “contrive charges” against Trump and “cast ominous aspersions on his close advisers.”</p><p> “With respect to questions as to whether Dr. Eastman is involved in plea bargaining, the answer is no,” Burnham said. “But if he were invited to plea bargain with either state or federal prosecutors, he would decline. The fact is, if Dr. Eastman is indicted, he will go to trial. If convicted, he will appeal.”</p><p> Clark and a lawyer for Chesebro didn&#39;t immediately return calls seeking comment. A lawyer for Powell declined to comment. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=467377AE-2B50-4F03-8708-ED3A50658DCE&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Ftrump-indictment-jack-smith-2020-election-4b351abf&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Special counsel Jack Smith said Tuesday that Donald Trump was charged with four crimes, including conspiring to defraud the US, for his actions that culminated in the Jan. 6, 2021, attack on the Capitol. Photo: Saul Loeb/AFP/Getty Images<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>In Smith&#39;s separate probe of Trump&#39;s handling of government documents, prosecutors recently added three new counts, alleging Trump and his aides sought to have surveillance footage from the club deleted so that it couldn&#39;t be turned over to a grand jury. A federal judge has scheduled the trial in that case to begin on May 20, 2024.</p><p> The original June indictment in the documents case charged Trump with 37 counts on seven different charges, including willful retention of national-defense information, withholding a record, false statements and conspiracy to obstruct.</p><p> Despite his compounding legal problems, Trump has remained the clear front-runner for the GOP nomination as he has portrayed himself as the victim of a broad effort to keep him out of office. He has seen fundraising spikes surrounding his two previous indictments, and most of his Republican rivals for the nomination have joined in criticizing his prosecution.</p><p> Attorney General Merrick Garland has denied that the Justice Department&#39;s investigations are politically motivated—he wasn&#39;t in Washington on Tuesday but was roughly 175 miles away in Philadelphia, attending an anticrime event. He appointed Smith, whom he called a “veteran career prosecutor,” in November 2022 as special counsel to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-presidential-campaign-following-arraignment-4e4aeae6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">insulate the probe</a> and give it a degree of independence from the agency&#39;s political appointees.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Isaac Yu and Byron Tau contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Sadie Gurman at <a href="mailto:sadie.gurman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">sadie.gurman@wsj.com</a> and Aruna Viswanatha at <a href="mailto:aruna.viswanatha@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">aruna.viswanatha@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/a12c152d-cc1a-4b9e-a744-8a0d292d80a8.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 02 Aug 2023 01:46:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-indictment-jack-smith-2020-election-4b351abf</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-indictment-jack-smith-2020-election-4b351abf<author><![CDATA[Sadie GurmanAruna Viswanatha]]></author><category> trump legal</category><category> Assault</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Civil Unrest</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>欺诈罪</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>社会问题</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>Trump Legal</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> assault</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>civil unrest</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>社会</category><category>community</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>欺诈罪</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>社会问题</category><category>选举</category><category>总统选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Why Middle-Aged Americans Aren’t Going Back to Church]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Americans in their 40s and 50s often identify with a religion, but they&#39;re also in the thick of raising kids, caring for aging parents and juggling demanding jobs <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827955/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Daisy Korpics/The Wall Street Journal; iStock(2) <span>Daisy Korpics/The Wall Street Journal; iStock(2)</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001102357"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001102357"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/clare-ansberry"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/B3-BS880_ANSBER_A_20180913112938.jpg" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/clare-ansberry" itemprop="url" rel="author">Clare Ansberry</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 1, 2023 9:00 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/church-attendance-religion-generation-x-6ee5f11d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Church attendance for Gen Xers has dropped off more dramatically than other age groups.</p><p> Americans in their 40s and 50s often identify with a religion, but they&#39;re also in the thick of raising kids, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/avoid-the-sibling-resentment-trap-in-caring-for-an-aging-parent-d79c33ec?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">caring for aging parents</a> and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/would-life-be-better-if-you-worked-less-3f49e69a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">juggling demanding jobs</a> that spill into the weekend. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/easter-holiday-churches-covid-8699f4b0?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">During the pandemic</a> , many got out of the habit of going regularly to religious services and didn&#39;t resume. Some had been drifting away before or became disillusioned by church scandals or positions on social issues in recent years.</p><p> The percentage of people ages 39 to 57 who attended a worship service during the week, either in person or online, fell to 28% in 2023, down from 41% in 2020, according to a survey this year. This was the largest percentage-point drop of all age groups examined in the survey of 2,000 adults conducted by the Cultural Research Center at Arizona Christian University. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827716?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Marlon Eddins, 45 years old, who lives in Memphis, Tenn., and works in the automotive industry, attends church about half as often as he did before the pandemic. “I got into the habit of not going,” says the father of a 25- and 19-year-old. “I go to church, but not as often as I probably should.”</p><p> He and his family changed churches and now attend a nondenominational church, rather than the Baptist church of his youth. “There&#39;s a different vibe and a culture shift,” he says, adding that he retains his core Baptist beliefs. “When you got faith, you got faith. I just don&#39;t think going every Sunday makes you who you are.”</p><p> The percentage of Gen Xers who worship weekly is now as low as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-surprising-surge-of-faith-among-young-people-424220bd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">millennial</a> s, according to the Cultural Research Center survey. Baby boomers and people ages 77 and older had the highest attendance rates, at 38% and 53% respectively.</p><p> “No generation endured greater spiritual turbulence than Gen X during the pandemic,” says George Barna, director of research at the Cultural Research Center, which also found drops in other religious practices and beliefs among Gen Xers.</p><p> Church attendance levels have been declining for decades across generations, with less than half of US adults belonging to houses of worship in 2020, compared with 70% in 1999, according to Gallup.</p><p> The drop-off for those in their 40s and 50s has been building, says Josh Packard, a 45-year-old sociologist of religion, who has researched changing forms of religious expression. Parents often attend church or temples to get their kids through certain religious milestones, including confirmation and bat mitzvahs, Packard says. “Then, after that, it starts to wane more every year,” he says. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827956?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Josh Packard and son at church in Colorado.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Josh Packard</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Trisha Taylor, 59, an ordained minister and church consultant in Houston, said people in their 40s and 50s often grew up in one church and never questioned going until the pandemic, which gave them time to examine their beliefs and practices. Some are disenchanted by polarization within churches and positions over many issues, including <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/young-people-say-disconnect-keeps-them-from-church-11635163200?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">gay rights,</a> which may affect their children.</p><p> John Newman, 41, no longer attends or donates to church, but will still respond “Catholic” on a survey and supports Catholic schools and their sports programs. Newman, who went to Catholic schools, stopped going to church in his 30s, when he says that a new priest marginalized people who were gay, living out of wedlock or divorced.</p><p> “I&#39;m not interested in hearing those sermons,” says Newman, who lives in the Chicago area.</p><p> Some people who study religion liken the drop-off in attendance and involvement to the workplace phenomenon called <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/if-your-gen-z-co-workers-are-quiet-quitting-heres-what-that-means-11660260608?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">quiet quitting</a> .</p><p> While average attendance, including online, has rebounded from the pandemic in many congregations, deeper participation is still lagging, says David Brubaker, a professor at Eastern Mennonite University and organizational consultant. Volunteering fell to about 20% of church membership in March 2022 from about 40% in early 2020, according to the Hartford Institute for Religion Research.</p><p> “Congregants may show up on a Saturday or Sunday but are less apt to jump in and help,” he says, adding that members will stay and engage if they find meaning and connection. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827954?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Church attendance levels have been declining for decades across generations, with less than half of US adults belonging to houses of worship in 2020, compared with 70% in 1999, according to Gallup.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：iStock</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> People remain on membership rolls, but stop volunteering, says Packard. In many cases, they continue making donations until their credit card expires. If asked, they continue to describe themselves as Protestant, Jewish or another denomination.</p><p> “It&#39;s not like they are walking away, saying, &#39;I&#39;m now an atheist and don&#39;t believe,&#39;” he says. “They still believe in a God and live life with purpose but are done with the institutional church.”</p><p> Ginger Harris, 51, a nonprofit executive and former Southern Baptist missionary, stopped attending her Southern Baptist church over changes including restrictions on women ministers. She&#39;s not sure she would have been able to leave a church, where she was actively involved, hosting Bible study groups in her home, at a younger age.</p><p> “I was at a place of maturity and was able to let go of that rigidness,” says Harris, who now attends weekly Zoom services from an Episcopal church and gatherings in the home of a local progressive Baptist pastor.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> SHARE YOUR THOUGHTS</h4><p> <em>Why do you think Gen Xers are becoming less religious? Join the conversation below.</em></p></div></div><p> Many Gen Xers say going to church remains a priority. Jeannetta McElroy, 44, attends services regularly at a nondenominational church in Chicago. “It&#39;s like my family,” says McElroy, whose two sons, 24 and 17, often join her.</p><p> McElroy returned to in-person services in January and before then had been participating online. She feels it&#39;s important to be there in person, but she has noticed some friends her age going less often. “Their lives are just busy with jobs and kids,” says McElroy.</p><p> Nicole Nuehring, 44, of Utah, sees many Latter-day Saint friends stepping away, which she attributes to disillusionment over scandals that they read about on social media and time away from church services during the pandemic to question why they were going in the first place. “It was easier to quiet-quit,” says Nuehring, who doesn&#39;t attend church and didn&#39;t as a child.</p><p> Many of her peers are exhausted from hectic work and family lives, she says. While older generations also went through demanding stages of life, they remained more involved in their churches.</p><p> “Church was an anchor, where it&#39;s not anymore,” she says.</p><p> Write to Clare Ansberry at <a href="mailto:clare.ansberry@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">clare.ansberry@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 02 Aug 2023 01:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/church-attendance-religion-generation-x-6ee5f11d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/church-attendance-religion-generation-x-6ee5f11d<author><![CDATA[Clare Ansberry]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>Living/Lifestyle</category><category> Parenting/Parenthood</category><category>宗教</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>community</category><category> living</category><category>生活方式</category><category>养育子女</category><category>parenthood</category><category>宗教</category></item></channel></rss>